LangGraph is a library for building stateful, multi-actor applications with LLM, used to build agent-driven, multi-agent workflows. Compared to other LLM frameworks, it offers these key benefits: cycles, controllability, and persistence. LangGraph allows you to define flows that involve cycles, essential for most agent architectures, which sets it apart from DAG-based solutions. As a very low-level framework, it provides fine-grained control over both the flow and state of your application, which is crucial for building reliable agents. Additionally, LangGraph includes built-in persistence, allowing for advanced memory and human-intervention features.

Below are implementation examples for key components of the proposed LangGraph.js solution, which are aligned with the suggested improvements. Each example highlights specific functionality that can be incorporated to improve the library.

Example 1: Predefined Templates
// plantillas.json
{
  "weatherInquiry": {
    "description": "Climate query flow",
    "nodes": [
      {
        "id": "userInput",
        "type": "HumanMessage",
        "prompt": "What is the city to check the weather?"
      },
      {
        "id": "climateCheck",
        "type": "ToolNode",
        "tool": "weatherTool"
      },
      {
        "id": "finalResponse",
        "type": "AIMessage",
        "response": "Weather information has been provided."
      }
    ],
    "edges": [
      {"from": "userInput", "to": "climateCheck"},
      {"from": "climateCheck", "to": "finalResponse"}
    ]
  }
}

// Using the template in the code
import templateData from './plantillas.json';
const workflow = new StateGraph(StateAnnotation)
  .addNode(templateData.weatherInquiry.nodes)
  .addEdge(templateData.weatherInquiry.edges);

Example 2: Configuration Wizards

// Setup Wizard in a React App
import React, { useState } from 'react';

function GraphConfigAssistant() {
  const [nodeType, setNodeType] = useState('');

  const handleSubmit = () => {
    // Generates the node and adds it to the graph
    const newNode = createNode(nodeType); // function that generates a node according to the selected type
    addNodeToGraph(newNode); // function to add the node to the graph under construction
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <h3>Graph Configuration Wizard</h3>
      <select onChange={(e) => setNodeType(e.target.value)}>
        <option value="userInput">User input</option>
        <option value="toolNode">Tool</option>
      </select>
      <button onClick={handleSubmit}>Add Node</button>
    </div>
  );
}

Example 3: Lazy Loading of Nodes

// Function to load nodes on demand
async function lazyLoadNode(nodeId) {
  const nodeConfig = await fetchNodeConfig(nodeId); // Function that gets the node configuration based on its ID
  return new ToolNode(nodeConfig.tools);
}

// Execution of the graph using lazy loading
const workflow = new StateGraph(StateAnnotation);
const initialState = await workflow.invoke(initialInput);

if (shouldTriggerLazyLoad(initialState)) {
  const additionalNode = await lazyLoadNode('newToolNode');
  workflow.addNode(additionalNode);
}

// Simple algorithm to detect when human intervention is needed
function shouldPauseForUser(state) {
  const lastMessage = state.messages[state.messages.length - 1];
  return lastMessage.isAmbiguous || lastMessage.needsClarification;
}

Example 4: Contextual Interactions
// Implementation in the workflow
const workflow = new StateGraph(StateAnnotation)
  .addNode("agent", callModel)
  .addConditionalEdges("agent", shouldContinue)
  .addConditionalEdges("agent", shouldPauseForUser);

// Wrapper for an external API - Twilio SMS
import { tool } from '@langchain/core/tools';
import twilio from 'twilio';

const sendSmsTool = tool(async ({ to, message }) => {
  const client = twilio(twilioAccountSid, twilioAuthToken);
  await client.messages.create({ body: message, to });
}, {
  name: 'sendSms',
  description: 'Envia un mensaje SMS utilizando Twilio',
  schema: z.object({
    to: z.string().describe('N√∫mero de tel√©fono al que enviar el SMS.'),
    message: z.string().describe('El mensaje que se enviar√°.'),
  }),
});

Example 5: Integration with External Tools

// Add the tool node to the workflow
const tools = [sendSmsTool];
const toolNode = new ToolNode(tools);
workflow.addNode('sendSmsNode', toolNode);

Example 6: Interactive Documentation

// Using Jupyter Notebooks for executable examples
# In Jupyter notebook content
import langgraph as lg

# Initialize the graph
graph = lg.StateGraph()

# Add a node
graph.add_node("Entrada Usuario", callback=user_input_function)

# Initialize the graph
result = graph.run(initial_state)
print(result)

These examples are representative of how the technical implementation of the suggested features to improve LangGraph.js can be carried out. Each example focuses on various aspects, from the user interface to integration with external APIs, offering a clear path towards implementing a more robust and accessible solution.

Description:
This PR implements an SDK for Vercel AI in the Solana Agent Kit. A new Action interface was introduced that allows for the creation and handling of various actions using the Vercel AI model. Changes made include the definition of a handler to process requests, a validator function to ensure valid input, and documented usage examples.

Changes Made:
Action Interface Definition:
The Action interface has been implemented that structures the actions to be executed:

CopyReplit
interface Action {
name: string;
similes: string[];
description: string;
examples: ActionExample[][];
handler: Handler;
validate: Validator;
}
Handler Implementation:
A handler has been created to execute query actions to the AI ‚Äã‚Äãmodel:

CopyReplit
const exampleHandler: Handler = async (input: any) => {
// Logic to handle the query
const response = await sendRequestToAIModel(input);
return response;
};
Validator Implementation:
A validation function has been added to verify the inputs:

CopyReplit
const exampleValidator: Validator = (input: any) => {
return typeof input === 'string' && input.length > 0;
};
Action Example:
Created an action example that uses the new SDK:

CopyReplit
const exampleAction: Action = {
name: "QueryAI",
similes: ["Ask AI", "Get AI Response"],
description: "Send a query to the Vercel AI model and receive a response.",
examples: [[{ input: "What is the weather like?" }, { output: "It's sunny." }]],
handler: exampleHandler,
validate: exampleValidator
};
Updated Documentation:
Documentation files have been updated to reflect new functionality and usage examples have been provided.

Implemented Tests:
Unit tests have been created to ensure the correct functioning of the handler and validator:

CopyReplit
test('Validate input', () => {
expect(exampleValidator("Valid input")).toBe(true);
expect(exampleValidator("")).toBe(false);
});

test('Handle action', async () => {
const response = await exampleHandler("What is the weather like?");
expect(response).toBeDefined();
});
Justification:
The implementation of this interface allows developers to interact more effectively with the Vercel AI model, offering a unified framework that facilitates the integration of new functionalities into the Solana agent kit. This improvement also promotes code reuse and better organization in the development of future integrations.

Requirements:
Node.js and project dependencies must be installed and up to date.
Tests can be run using the npm test command.
Conclusion:
I hope these changes will be helpful in improving the Solana Agent Kit. I remain available to make any required adjustments and to answer any questions that may arise during the review.

